</style>

<!-- HERO + TRUST BAR (unified ServiceHero) -->
<ServiceHero
  title="BBQ Grill Repair Across Southern California"
  subtitle="Same-day across LA, Orange, Ventura, San Bernardino & Riverside counties. Burner won't light, uneven heat, gas smell — portable grills, built-in outdoor kitchens, pellet grills. Lynx, Alfresco, Weber, Wolf, Fire Magic. Gas-certified, BHGS Licensed #A49573."
  heroImageTitle="BBQ Grill Repair"
/>

<!-- INTRO -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="intro-grid">
      <div class="intro-body">
        <p class="section-number">01 — About This Service</p>
        <h2 class="section-title">Southern California grills year-round. That means grills break down year-round — and we're out here constantly.</h2>

        <p>Most US cities grill seasonally — maybe five months a year. In Southern California — LA, Orange County, Ventura, the Inland Empire — the grill runs in January. It runs in March. It runs on a Tuesday evening in November because the weather is 68 degrees and there's no reason not to. That year-round use pattern means SoCal grills accumulate grease, wear, and corrosion at three to four times the rate of a grill in Chicago or Boston. A gas valve that would last eight years in Minnesota might fail in three here.</p>

        <p>We see a full range of BBQ grill repairs across SoCal — from the $350 Weber kettle on a Silver Lake apartment patio or a Long Beach condo balcony to the $12,000 Lynx built-in centerpiece of a Malibu, Newport Coast, or Westlake Village outdoor kitchen with its own dedicated gas line, refrigerator, and warming drawer. The diagnosis process is the same; the parts and complexity differ. Gas-certified technicians on every gas grill call. Weber parts on the van. Luxury brand parts sourced same-day for Alfresco, Fire Magic, Twin Eagles, and Capital. BHGS Licensed #A49573.</p>

        <div class="alert-gas">
          <div class="ag-label">⚠️ Gas Smell? Call Your Gas Utility First.</div>
          <p>Turn off the grill and the gas supply valve. Call your gas utility — <strong>SoCalGas at 1-800-427-2200</strong> across most of LA, OC, Ventura, and parts of SB; <strong>Southwest Gas at 1-877-860-6020</strong> for Riverside, Anaheim, Long Beach, and parts of SB. They verify the source and confirm the area is safe at no charge. Then call us at {phone} for the repair. Gas utility first, appliance repair second.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <aside class="sticky-cta">
        <div class="cta-label">BBQ Repair — Same Day</div>
        <a href={phoneHref} class="cta-phone">{phone}</a>
        <a href={phoneHref} class="btn-cta">Call Now — Same Day</a>
        <a href="/book" class="btn-cta" style="background:#222; margin-top:-4px;">Schedule Online</a>
        <div class="cta-sub">Mon–Sun 7am–9pm · Gas-certified techs</div>
        <hr class="cta-divider" />
        <ul class="cta-detail">
          <li>Diagnostic: $89 — waived with repair</li>
          <li>BHGS Licensed #A49573</li>
          <li>Gas-certified technicians</li>
          <li>Weber parts on the van</li>
          <li>Luxury brand parts same-day</li>
          <li>5-county SoCal coverage</li>
        </ul>
      </aside>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- LUXURY vs STANDARD -->
<section class="section section-black">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">02 — Two Very Different Repairs</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">A $400 Weber and a $10,000 Lynx both need repair. The approach is completely different.</h2>
    <p class="lead">Knowing which type you have before you call helps us bring the right parts and set realistic expectations on cost and timeline.</p>

    <div class="grill-split">
      <div class="gs-card luxury">
        <div class="gs-badge badge-luxury">🏡 Luxury Built-In</div>
        <h3>Outdoor kitchen grills — Lynx, Alfresco, Fire Magic, Wolf, Twin Eagles</h3>
        <p>Permanent installation with dedicated gas line, often infrared burners, rotisserie systems, and integrated lighting. Complex ignition electronics. Parts are expensive and may require ordering. Common in Malibu, Bel Air, Beverly Hills, Pacific Palisades, Newport Coast, Newport Beach, Westlake Village, and Temecula wine-country outdoor kitchens.</p>
        <p>Repair investment makes sense — a $400 repair on a $10,000 grill that runs perfectly for another 10 years is straightforward math.</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Infrared burner replacement</li>
          <li>Gas manifold and valve assembly</li>
          <li>Electronic ignition module</li>
          <li>Rotisserie motor and spit</li>
          <li>Dedicated gas line inspection</li>
          <li>Full outdoor kitchen service</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="gs-card standard">
        <div class="gs-badge badge-standard">🔥 Portable & Freestanding</div>
        <h3>Weber, Napoleon, Char-Broil, Traeger, Nexgrill</h3>
        <p>Freestanding or portable grills on a cart or patio. Self-contained propane or natural gas. Standard ignition systems. Parts are widely available and usually in stock on our service vehicles. Fast repairs in most cases.</p>
        <p>We're honest about repair vs. replace: a grill that's 10+ years old with a seized burner manifold may cost more to repair than to replace with a new unit. We'll tell you directly.</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Igniter and spark module</li>
          <li>Burner replacement</li>
          <li>Gas valve and regulator</li>
          <li>Heat plates and grates</li>
          <li>Control knobs and electronics</li>
          <li>Pellet auger and controller (Traeger)</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- PROBLEMS -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">03 — Common Failures</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What our technicians diagnose most often in SoCal BBQ grills</h2>

    <div class="problems-grid">
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Burner Won't Ignite</h3>
        <p>Three causes: failed igniter/spark module (no click sound), clogged burner ports from grease and carbon buildup (spark present but no sustained flame), or failed gas valve. In SoCal's year-round grilling environment, clogged burner ports from accumulated grease are the most common single cause. Try cleaning the ports with a wire brush before calling — it solves the problem about 30% of the time without any parts replacement.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Uneven Heat / Hot and Cold Spots</h3>
        <p>Blocked or partially clogged burner ports create uneven flame distribution — one section runs hot, another barely heats. Failed or warped heat plates (the stainless or ceramic shields above the burners) that are supposed to distribute heat evenly can also cause this. On infrared grills, a cracked ceramic tile creates a dead zone that's disproportionately noticeable.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Weak Flame / Low Heat Output</h3>
        <p>Failed pressure regulator — the device between the propane tank and the grill that maintains consistent gas pressure. A regulator in "bypass mode" (a safety state triggered by a detected pressure anomaly) restricts gas flow to a trickle. Disconnect the tank, wait 30 seconds, and reconnect — sometimes this resets the regulator. If the problem persists, the regulator needs replacement.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Excessive Flare-Ups</h3>
        <p>Grease accumulation in the drip tray, on the heat plates, or inside the burner box. Flare-ups are a fire risk beyond being a cooking problem — grease fire inside a grill cabinet can damage gas lines and ignition wiring. We clean grease accumulation as part of every grill service visit and check that drip trays are properly positioned and undamaged.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Rust and Corrosion</h3>
        <p>SoCal's marine layer — particularly in coastal neighborhoods from Santa Monica to Malibu in LA, Newport Beach to Laguna in OC, and the Ventura coastal corridor — deposits salt moisture on outdoor equipment year-round. Stainless steel grills resist this better than painted steel, but coastal salt air attacks even high-grade stainless at weld points and cast iron grates. Surface rust on grates is a cleaning and maintenance issue; structural rust on the burner box or frame is a replacement indicator.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Pellet Grill Not Heating (Traeger / Pit Boss)</h3>
        <p>Pellet grills have a different failure mode than gas grills: the auger motor that feeds pellets to the fire pot, the igniter rod that lights the pellets, and the temperature controller that manages the whole system. The most common failure is a failed igniter rod — the pellets load correctly but the rod doesn't generate enough heat to light them. Wet pellets from moisture exposure are also a common SoCal-specific issue (coastal humidity + IE summer monsoonal moisture cycles).</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

