<!-- RECENT REPAIRS -->
<section class="section section-black">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">06 — Recent Repairs</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What our technicians actually fixed recently</h2>

    <div class="repairs-grid">
      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Malibu · Estate · Lynx 42-Inch Built-In Gas Grill</div>
        <h3>"Main burners won't ignite — left side completely dead since last week"</h3>
        <p>Failed electronic ignition module on the left burner bank of a Lynx 42-inch built-in in a Malibu outdoor kitchen. The module controlled three of six burners. When it failed, those burners had no spark signal — the gas was flowing correctly but nothing to light it. The homeowner had been using a long lighter to manually ignite those burners, which works but creates a dangerous momentary gas accumulation before ignition.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Replaced Lynx ignition module and electrode assemblies for the affected burner bank. Tested all six burners through multiple ignition cycles. Also found the drip tray positioned incorrectly — it had shifted and was allowing grease to accumulate under the burner box rather than draining. Repositioned and cleaned. Noted that the outdoor kitchen refrigerator below the grill was running louder than it should — owner asked us to check it while on-site; found dirty condenser coils, cleaned on the same visit. Full service: $380 grill repair, $120 refrigerator service.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Newport Coast (OC) · Bluff Home · Alfresco 30-Inch ALXE Gas Grill</div>
        <h3>"Grill has been burning hot on the right and barely warm on the left for months"</h3>
        <p>Two separate issues on an Alfresco ALXE built-in at a Newport Coast bluff home: a clogged right-side burner running at too-high output because the ports were partially blocked by grease carbon (concentrated heat in a smaller area), and a failing gas valve on the left side restricting flow to approximately 40% of spec. The combination created a pronounced cooking gradient — steak seared perfectly on the right, barely cooked on the left — that the homeowner had been working around for the entire summer. Coastal salt air had also accelerated burner-port corrosion.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Deep-cleaned right-side burner ports with commercial solvent — removed significant carbon buildup from high-heat cooking with the grill cover down. Replaced left-side gas valve with OEM Alfresco part. Verified BTU output across all burners using temperature recovery timing as proxy — both sides within 5% of each other after repair. Tested through three cooking cycles with thermometer probes at both ends of the grill. Homeowner had adjusted their cooking technique for months to compensate — they were genuinely surprised how evenly the grill performed after repair.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Silver Lake · Apartment Building Rooftop · Weber Spirit E-310</div>
        <h3>"Grill won't get above 250°F — even on full blast"</h3>
        <p>Regulator in bypass mode on a Weber Spirit E-310. The propane regulator had detected a rapid pressure change (from a tank being opened too quickly) and entered its safety bypass state, restricting gas flow to prevent a potential runaway pressure event. The grill appeared to be functioning — igniter working, flame present — but couldn't reach cooking temperature. The tenant had been using the grill in this degraded state for two weeks thinking the burners needed replacement.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Diagnosed regulator bypass by checking flame size against spec and testing gas pressure at the manifold. Performed the regulator reset procedure (disconnect tank, open all burner valves for 30 seconds to bleed pressure, close all valves, reconnect tank slowly). Regulator released from bypass mode. Grill reached 550°F on high within 8 minutes — correct for the model. No parts needed. Showed the tenant the reset procedure for future reference. Also cleaned the grill — found significant grease accumulation in the drip tray that was close to causing a grease fire problem. Full service call including cleaning: $89 + $65 cleaning, $154 total.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Westlake Village (Ventura) · Backyard · Traeger Pro 780 Pellet Grill</div>
        <h3>"Traeger not heating up — fan runs but never gets above 100°F"</h3>
        <p>Failed igniter rod on a Traeger Pro 780 in a Westlake Village backyard. The auger was feeding pellets correctly and the fan was running (creating airflow for combustion), but the igniter rod — the element that heats to ~800°F to light the pellets — had failed. The pellets were accumulating in the fire pot unlit, and the fan was just pushing ambient air through. The owner had run the grill through three start attempts, dumping an increasing amount of unlit pellets into the fire pot each time.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Replaced igniter rod with Traeger OEM part. Cleared the accumulated unlit pellets from the fire pot (an important step — relighting over a full pile of pellets can cause a temperature spike). Ran the startup sequence through a full temperature climb to 350°F and held for 20 minutes monitoring temperature curve. Also checked the RTD temperature probe — found it reading 15°F low, calibrated in the controller settings. Pellet grill producing correct temperatures within spec after repair. Advised owner on storing pellets in a sealed container — Conejo Valley's humidity cycling had been partially moistening the pellets, which affects ignitability.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

